[A] Figures on atypical pneumonia 28 Mar 2003
<http://www.info.gov.hk/dh/new/index.htm>
The following is jointly issued by the Department of Health and the
Hospital Authority:
As of 1 PM 28 Mar 2003, a total of 425 people with pneumonia symptoms have
been admitted to public hospitals. The 58 additional patients reported
today include 4 healthcare workers and 34 patients from Amoy Garden. The
remaining 20 were new patients and contacts of patients with atypical
pneumonia.
As at today, 25 patients have been discharged from hospitals. A total of 45
patients are receiving treatment in the intensive care unit.
The breakdown of figures is as follows:
Total Admissions (The numbers in bracket are those with pneumonia symptoms)
Health care workers of Hospitals/Clinics and medical students 153 (153)
12 of the patients were discharged
Patients, family members & visitors 272 (272)
13 of the patients were discharged
Total admission 425 (425)
25 were discharged

[B] Health Surveillance for airline passengers 28 Mar 2003
A spokesman for the Department of Health (DH) on 28 Mar 2003 called on
passengers who had travelled from Beijing to Hong Kong in flight CA 111(Air
China) on 21 Mar 2003 or in flight CX 510(Cathay Pacific) from Hong Kong to
Taipei on the 21 Mar 2003 to call DH's hotline for atypical pneumonia (2961
8968) for health advice and surveillance.
The plea was made as DH's investigation found that 4 Taiwan passengers who
had taken these 2 flights developed symptoms of SARS during their stay in
Beijing. Investigation also revealed that they went to Beijing on flight
CA 112 on 15 Mar 2003. A number of passengers in flight CA 112 were
confirmed to have contracted with atypical pneumonia earlier this week. It
is suspected that the 4 Taiwan passengers contracted the disease from a
73-year-old passenger in flight CA 112 on their way to Beijing.
DH has informed the Airport Authority and the 2 airlines concerned. Advice
was also given to the airline concerned to disinfect the airplanes. DH is
tracing the crew members and passengers who had taken these 2 flights, for
surveillance purposes.
The spokesman reminded members of the public who have respiratory symptoms
including fever, chills, malaise, and cough to avoid traveling by plane
before recovery.
[These advisories are consistent with the now global recommendation for
pre-boarding screening of airline passengers for symptoms compatible with
SARS coming from areas with known local transmission. These cases do not
as yet suggest a more widespread easier transmission, as sitting close to
an individual who is actively coughing for several hours on an airline
flight would still be classified as "close contact". - Mod.MPP]
[C] Enhanced measures to control infectious disease 28 Mar 2003
A spokesman for the Department of Health (DH) on 28 Mar 2003 called on
members of the public who have paid visits to Metropole Hotel on 21-22 Feb
2003 or the Prince of Wales Hospital (PWH) on or after 1 Mar 2003,
excluding staff working in PWH, to contact them for health surveillance.
The spokesman said in order to enhance measures to control atypical
pneumonia, DH has converted 4 clinics into designated medical centres (DMC)
for daily surveillance of contacts of confirmed atypical pneumonia cases.
The 4v DMC are Pamela Youde Child Assessment Centre (Shatin); South Kwai
Chung Jockey Club Polyclinic; Shek Kip Mei Health Centre, and Sai Ying Pun
Jockey Club Clinic. They will be operated from 9 am to 5 pm daily, starting
31 Mar 2003.
The spokesman said that people who are identified to be close contacts of
patients suffering from atypical pneumonia are required to report each day
for check-up at one of these DMCs for 10 consecutive days. "Surveillance
of the health condition of these individuals will be made accordingly. If
they have developed symptoms of the disease, they will be admitted to
hospital for isolation and treatment. People who had close contact with
these patients should stay at home as far as possible and should not go out
unless it is absolutely necessary," the spokesman said. [This appears to
be a contradiction, as in order to report to one of the 4 designated DMCs,
these individuals will be leaving their homes and travelling to the DMCs,
many of whom might be travelling by public transportation. - Mod.MPP]
DH will send letters to all close contacts to ask them to attend one of the
DMCs for check-up. To ensure that every close contact would be put under
health surveillance, DH will set up a special hotline 187 2222 to answer
enquiries from this group of people. The hotline will be operated between 2
PM and 6 PM 29 Mar 2003 and from 9 am to 5 pm from 30 Mar 2003 onwards. DH
has the power to enforce these mandatory measures whenever necessary.
Close contact means persons having cared for, having lived with, or having
had direct contact with respiratory secretions and body fluids of a person
with severe acute respiratory syndrome. Close contacts are, therefore,
mainly household contacts and those caring for the case. Social contact
implies persons who have had contact with an individual with severe acute
respiratory syndrome but do not fit the definition of close contact.
All co-workers and all visitors of cases in hospitals are social contacts.
If these social contacts had direct contact with respiratory secretions and
body fluids of a case, they are classified as close contact. Social
contacts with symptoms will be advised to attend one of the DMCs.
--
