Source: Health Canada SARS 28 Mar 2003 6:30 PM [edited]
<http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/english/protection/warnings/2003/2003_11update13.htm>

Update #13 - Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome
-------------------------
As of 28 Mar 2003, Health Canada has received reports of 37 individuals who
have become ill with severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) in Ontario
and British Columbia. There have been 3 deaths in Canada. All Canadian
cases have occurred in persons who have traveled to Asia or had contact
with SARS cases in the household or in a health-care setting. The
information contained in this update is based on the best available
information Health Canada has at this time.
The details of the cases to date are as follows:
Ontario: 35 total cases. To date, all cases have occurred in close family
contacts of travelers returning from Hong Kong or in heath care workers who
have cared for these cases.
British Columbia: one person has been hospitalized with SARS after
returning from travel in southeast Asia.
Manitoba: one person has been hospitalized with SARS after returning from
travel in southeast Asia.
On 27 Mar 2003, the World Health Organization (WHO) recommended new
measures, related to international travel aimed at reducing the risk of
further international spread of severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS).
The measures proposed by WHO on the screening of passengers presenting for
international travel are under active consideration by Health Canada.
Health Canada has discussed this issue with the local airport authority in
Toronto, and we are putting together a plan. Health Canada is hoping to
have something in place in Toronto over the course of the weekend.
It is important to note that airlines operating international flights in
and out of Canada have been carrying out long-standing procedures to
prevent sick passengers from getting on airplanes.
Health Canada has deployed 5 epidemiologists to assist Toronto Public
Health and the Ontario Ministry of Health with the investigation of SARS
cases currently under investigation.The department has also provided
guidelines for infection control and recommendations on actions for public
health settings.
--
